<HEAD>

<TITLE>Flat Tax Fever -- Heritage </TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Anthony Rossello">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Anthony Rossello">
</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<H2> June/July Insider -- Flat Tax Fever </H2>
<HR>
<P>Although
it was a largely unknown academic concept just one year ago, the
flat tax today is one of the most talked about policy reforms
in Washington, in large part due to the efforts of House Majority
Leader Richard Armey of Texas. It now looks increasingly possible
that the current income tax system will be junked in favor of
this simple, fair, pro-growth plan. The present system suffers
from three major problems, each of which would be solved by the
flat tax:<P>
<ul>
<li>Problem #1: High tax rates that discourage work, savings,
and investment.Flat Tax Solution: The Armey flat tax replaces
the current discriminatory system of tax rates with a simple,
low rate that treats all taxpayers equally.<P>
<li>Problem #2: Needless
complexity that imposes $200 billion of compliance costs.Flat
Tax Solution: The Armey flat tax allows all taxpayers to fill
out their taxes on a postcardsized form.<P>
<li>Problem #3: Multiple taxation
of capital income that penalizes economic growth.Flat Tax Solution:
Not only are all individuals treated equally, so is all income.
No longer would some income escape taxation while other types
of income are subject to as many as four levels of taxation.
</ul><P>
The
flat tax solves all these problems by creating a tax system that
treats all citizens equally, rewards productive behavior, and
gets the government out of the business of using tax law to micromanage
the economy. The key benefits of the flat tax are:
<ul>
<li>Faster economic
growth: By reducing tax penalties against savings and investment,
a flat tax would spur increased work, saving, and investment.
If enactment of a flat tax boosted longterm annual growth by as
little as 0.5 percent, the income of an average family of four
after 10 years would be as much as $5,000 higher than if current
tax laws remained in place.<p>
<li>Instant wealth creation: According to
Harvard economist Dale Jorgenson, adoption of the flat tax would
boost national wealth by some $1 trillion. All incomeproducing
assets would rise in value since the flat tax would increase the
aftertax stream of income they generate.<p>
<li>Simplicity: One business
in 1992 had a tax return 21,000 pages long requiring 30 volumes.
Individual taxpayers are slightly better off, but the system still
imposes needless costs. Under a flat tax, all taxpayers, from
General Motors to John Doe, would be able to fill out their tax
return on a postcardsized form. Current compliance costs would
drop by tens of billions of dollars. <p>
<li>Fairness:  A flat tax would
treat people equally. A very wealthy taxpayer with 1,000 times
the income of another taxpayer would pay 1,000 times more in taxes.
No longer would the tax code penalize success and discriminate
on the basis of income.<p>
<li>End to micromanaging and political favoritism:
 The flat tax gets rid of all deductions, loopholes, credits,
and exemptions. Politicians would lose all ability to pick winners
and losers, reward friends and punish enemies, and use the tax
code to impose their values on the economy. According to Professor
Alvin Rabushka of Stanford, $100 billion of uneconomical investments
are made for tax purposes, funds that would be used to boost economic
growth under a flat tax.<p>
<li> Increased civil liberties: Under current
laws, those charged with murder have more rights than taxpayers
dealing with the IRS. With a simpler, fairer tax code, however,
infringements on freedoms and privacy would fall dramatically. <P>
<li>Political
feasibility: Unlike the national sales tax or value added tax, the
flat tax does not require either repealing the 16th amendment
or running the risk of creating an entirely new revenue source
for tax hungry politicians.The Heritage Foundation has published
two papers on the flat tax: Jobs, Growth, Freedom, and
Fairness: Why America Needs a Flat Tax (Backgrounder #1035) and
A Brief Guide to the Flat Tax (Talking Points). Heritage
is also leading a flat tax working group comprised of more than
100 representatives of think tanks, congressional offices, trade
associations, citizens groups, and businesses. In addition to
broad discussions about status and strategy, the working group
has subcommittees designed to address key issues involving the
media, public awareness, transition problems, and Capitol Hill.
House Speaker Newt Gingrich and Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole
have founded a "Tax Reform and Economic Growth" commission
charged with developing a fair and simple tax system. Heritage
President <a href="/heritage/staff/feulner.html">Ed Feulner</a> will serve as one of 13 appointees, as well
as the vice-chairman of the commission.<p>
<a href="/heritage/staff/mitchell.htm"> Dan Mitchell.</a><p>
 Dan Mitchell
is the McKenna Senior Fellow in Political Economy at The Heritage
Foundation.
<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></BODY>



