<head><title>Hot -Issues - Whitewater-3/22/96- ACU</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<h2>Hot Issues<p>
Whitewater</h2>
<br>
Friday, March 22, 1996
<p>
</center>



<hr>The following letter from ACU Chairman David Keene was delivered to the United State Senate on March 
18, 1996:<br>                 
        <p>
        
        Dear Senator:<br>
        <p>

        On behalf of the more than one million members and supporters of the American
        Conservative Union, I urge you to support an unlimited extension of the Special
        Whitewater Investigative Committee when the matter comes to the Senate floor this week.<p>
        
        While it is undeniably true that the Whitewater investigation has been going on for quite
        some time, it is also undeniably true that many in the Clinton White House and the
        Administration have displayed a callous, flagrant disregard for the subpoenas served on
        them.  On numerous occasions, documents subpoenaed months and even years ago have
        miraculously been &quot;discovered&quot; out of the blue.  Just in the past ten weeks, this has
        happened on four separate occasions, with the most recent &quot;discovery&quot; coming just a few
        days ago, when the White House released Counsel Bruce Lindsey's notes of a meeting
        long past.<p>
        
        No rational person could observe this pattern developing and not question whether or not
        the White House was complying fully with the Senate investigation, as the President
        promised it would.  Instead, it looks as if the White House has something to hide, and that
        someone there believes that if they just hold out long enough, the Senate committee will
        run out of time and money, and the danger -- whatever it might be -- will have passed.
        
        For that reason, we urge you to support not only an extension of the Whitewater
        Committee, but an indefinite extension.  Putting a time limit on it -- as some Democratic
        Senate leaders have suggested -- would merely tell anyone continuing to hold back
        documents how much longer they had to hide them before the threat was passed.<p>
        
        The American people want this investigation concluded, but they also want it concluded
        with no doubts left as to the facts of the matter.  Otherwise, the time and money spent
        already would be a waste.<p>
       
<Pre>
                          Yours sincerely,
        
        
               

                          David A. Keene
                              Chairman
</pre>
<p>
[<a href="/conservatives/">ACU Home</a>]<p>
</body>
</html>
        
                              David A. Keene
                              Chairman
        
        
        
