<HEAD>
<TITLE>Hot Issues - Immigration Reform - 3/20/96 - ACU</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
      <center>
<h2>Hot Issues<p>
        Immigration Reform          </h2>            
       

                                 <BR>


        Wednesday, March 20, 1996:

        <P></center>


        

        On behalf of the more than one million members
and supporters of the American

        Conservative Union, I'm writing to share
our concerns regarding the controversial issue of

        worker verification hotlines as contained
in HR 2202, the immigration reform bill you will

        be considering today and tomorrow.  We oppose
such hotlines, and urge you to oppose them

        as well.  Specifically, I urge you to oppose
the Gallegly amendment, and to support the

        Chabot amendment instead.

   <P>     

        The original version of the bill contained
language mandating a national employment

        verification pilot program, through the institution
of an 800-number hotline attached to a

        database.  Critics rightfully referred to
this as a &quot;1-800-BIG BROTHER&quot; number.

<P>        

        The worker verification provisions in the
original bill have been diluted somewhat.  Instead

        of a mandatory national program, the underlying
legislation now calls for a &quot;voluntary&quot;

        program in which employers could call a national
database to verify whether or not

        prospective workers were eligible for employment.

<P>        

        But what is the point of establishing a pilot
program, on either a mandatory or voluntary

        basis, if not to test its efficacy?  If it
fails, it will have been merely a waste of time and

        money.  But if it succeeds, the likelihood
is great that a move would be made in a future

        Congress to mandate the program nationally
-- something we oppose outright.

<P>        

        To begin, we have a strong philosophical
objection to the entire concept that individuals and

        private employees must phone the Federal
Government to ask permission to work. 

        Moreover, we have serious concerns about
where this might lead.  Once a national

        employee verification hotline is established,
we're only one short step away from national

        identification cards, to &quot;ease&quot;
the burden on the hotline and further combat fraud.  (In fact,

        we've noted with some dismay the establishment
of just such a federal identification card in

        the original version of the companion Senate
legislation, S. 269.)

<P>        

        In addition to our pure philosophical objections,
there are also practical considerations.  As

        we read the legislation, it appears to us
that the heaviest burden likely would fall on those

        businesses that seek to abide by the law;
those who knowingly and regularly flout the law

        by hiring illegal aliens would be no more
likely to abide by this law than they would be

        likely to abide by current law.  Thus, just
as in the case of the Brady Bill (which merely

        mandates that law-abiding citizens must wait
to purchase a hand gun, while criminals are

        not deterred at all from purchasing such
weapons), it is the law-abiding citizens who pay the

        price.

<P>        

        Small businesses do not have the staff or
the resources to keep up with the new mandate. 

        Many would be literally snowed under with
the new requirement.  Those who survive the

        new regulatory burden may see their colleagues'
distress and conclude that disobeying the

        law is a cost of doing business -- thereby
taking law-abiding small business owners and

        turning them into criminals.  Is that what
we want?

        <P>

        The Gallegly amendment would re-institute
the mandatory nature of the verification pilot

        program, while the Chabot amendment would
eliminate the program altogether.  For that

        reason, we urge you to oppose the Gallegly
amendment, and support instead the Chabot

        amendment.  When even a president as liberal
as Bill Clinton says &quot;The era of Big

        Government is over,&quot; how can we justify
the creation of a Big Brother employment

        verification hotline -- even on a trial basis?
<P>
[ <a href="/conservative/">ACU Home</a> ]<P>
               
</BODY>

