<HEAD>

<TITLE>The State of the Revolution: 1996 -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<br>
<h2>The State of the Revolution</h2>
<P>

<small>
<P>
<a href="#intro">Introduction</a> by Hon. Vin Weber
<br>
<a href="#age">The Age of New Realities</a> by Hon. Newt Gingrich
<br>
<a href="#rev">The Conservative Revolution</a> by Hon. John Redwood
<br>
<a href="#japan">The Japanese Restoration</a> by Hon. Iwao Matsuda
<br>
<a href="#three">The Three Revolutions</a> by Hon. Preston Manning
</small>
<P>
<P>
<I>The following remarks were delivered at &quot;The New Majority:
 Democratic Governance in a Revolutionary Age&quot; conference,
hosted by The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation on January 22,
1996.  The conference explored the possibility of political realignment
and asked:  Is there a &quot;new majority&quot; taking shape in
America and other western-style democracies?  Who is part of the
new majority, what are its beliefs - and how is it related to
the transition from an industrial to an information-age economy?
 Which (if either) American political party is best positioned
to represent it?  And, what impact will it have on the 1996 presidential
election?</I>
<P>
<h3><a name="intro">Introduction</a></h3>
<B>by <a href="#webe">Vin Weber </a></B>
<P>
Along with the United States itself, America's key allies are
transforming themselves away from the industrial age that has
dominated the past century just as surely as they moved away from
the agrarian age in an earlier time.  While the outlines of the
new era are yet to be determined, we know that it will be overwhelmingly
influenced by the information technology that is now upon us -
every day we hear something new about the Internet, Cyberspace
and virtuality.
<P>
The private sector has been learning the lessons of the new age
for more than a decade. General Motors, IBM and AT&amp;T have
learned that bureaucratic, centralized organizations must be replaced
because success in the information age demands decentralization
and empowerment.  Government too must remake itself for a new
age.  The idea that programs run by a bureaucracy concentrated
in Washington, D.C. is the preferred method for addressing the
nation's problems is no longer tenable.
<P>
As the people remake government for the 21st century, three major
trends become clear: devolution, diffusion and connection. Devolution
is sending power and responsibility to the lowest level possible
for effective decision-making.  Shifting from Federal to state
or local control is just a trickle today. Diffusion is relying
on non-governmental organizations or individuals to perform many
of the functions government usurped during the industrial era.
 The use of vouchers, privatization, voluntary organizations,
charities and churches are among the tools of diffusion. The final
trend is connection. This has less to do with government than
with individuals. We must return to the sense of community we
once had.  The most important people are those closest to you.
You must want to help - and feel a responsibility for -  yourself,
your family, your friends and your neighbors.
<P>
Remaking government in such a manner is indeed a democratic revolution.
 Often times it appears that the leaders of such a revolution
are radicals, acting alone in the woods.  Yet if we look around
the world, we see that different cultures and political traditions
are facing basically the same set of facts as they too make the
transition to the information age. In bringing together the leading
agents of political change in America, Great Britain, Japan and
Canada, we found that to a remarkable degree their ideas reinforce
each other.  In their own way and working within their own political
traditions, they describe similar goals for achieving the best
form of government for the information age.
<P>
These leaders also demonstrate how important correct political
management is.  The degree of change required in government organization
is so great that delaying it, stifling it or trying to stop it
will only hurt citizens.  Yet in America, President Clinton has
adopted the rhetoric - &quot;the era of big government is over&quot;
- while actually governing in the opposite manner.  In Britain,
the democratic revolution is at risk by the Tory Prime Minister.
And in Canada, the Conservatives went from governing the country
to having only two seats in the Parliament after they failed to
offer the correct policies of progress.
<P>
As Americans debate the proper role of government in the 21st
century, it is important for them to see models of success and
failure.  By bringing together four remarkable leaders, we hope
to discover some lessons ourselves.
<P>
<h3><a name="age">The Age of New Realities</a></h3>
<B>by <a href="#ging">Newt Gingrich </a></B>
<P></a>
In thinking through what is similar that is driving Canada, Britain,
Japan and America, I think there are three large realities that
will shape everything else we're doing for a very long time.
<P>
The first is the world market.  The world market is going to impose
continuing pressure for competitive modification.  All of the
western democracies - and here I will include Japan as a western
democracy - are faced with the same challenge: how to become dramatically
more productive as societies in order to compete in a 21st century
market in which China and other countries such as Thailand, Pakistan
and India will be playing more and more competitive roles.   This
goes much beyond manufacturing, into the whole question of education,
of tax codes and of entrepreneurship.  The Europeans, frankly,
have been less successful at such adaptation, which is reflected
in very high unemployment rates.  Yet the world market will apply
continuing pressure, and America and Japan are going to face that
pressure fully as much as the Europeans.  
<P>
The second reality is the rise of the information age.  Alvin
and Heidi Tofler describe it as the Third Wave, and it is at least
comparable to the rise of the industrial world that Adam Smith
was writing about in the late 18th Century. It is a change so
large that it will force us to rethink everything we're doing.
 The degree to which we can do that in an open, positive, conscious
way will be dramatically better than if we just stumble into it.
The rise of an information age or of a Third Wave civilization
is going to affect every society on the planet, and I think all
of us have to get used to that and have to figure out therefore
what is it we're doing.  For instance, a new species was recently
discovered in Laos in the national park.  National parks are a
19th century American invention that have rapidly spread across
the planet.  They are an example of what happens as you go through
this kind of modification. All of us are going to find ways to
deal with the information age; they're going to turn out to be
remarkably similar over time, but those societies which are on
the cutting edge will have higher incomes and greater choices.
 Those societies which resist the information age will have lower
incomes and fewer choices.
<P>
The third thing challenging all of us is an expanding definition
of human.  If you go back to the 18th century, basically propertied
white males counted and everybody else was relatively less important.
Yet over the last 200 years, we've had a continually expanding
sense of what does it mean to be human.  As we get to a point
of including everybody and deciding that we're prepared to spend
resources to include them, we're going to be challenged with a
greater and greater intensity to deal with the question, how do
we include everyone to the fullest of their ability and how do
we compensate for those who might have been genetically or otherwise
disadvantaged?  
<P>
Those three factors, the world market, the information age and
the expanding definition of being human, are realities for all
societies and particularly for all democratic societies.  There
are also three facts that industrial societies in particular face.
<P>
The first fact is the failure of state central planning. The collapse
of the Soviet Empire demonstrated this most clearly.  Many of
our friends on the left bitterly regret that it failed and prefer
to ignore its demise.  The Clinton Administration is the last
stand in this country of a genuine belief that centralized planning
makes sense. But the fact is it just failed.  
<P>
The second fact is the failure of secular bureaucracy.  It turns
out that as ways of saving human beings, secular bureaucrats are
among the least successful.  We need to say that more often. 
For example, when our President talks about investing in education,
we should first say, all right, if you're spending $9,000 per
child in Washington, D.C., maybe the problem isn't money.  But
we're not willing to be blunt enough and tough enough about the
obvious failure of secular bureaucracy as a delivery system for
dramatically improving human beings.
<P>
The third fact is the failure of emphasizing redistribution over
production of wealth.  Going back in some ways to 19th century
French socialism, there has been a fascination with redistribution
of wealth, particularly by those who don't produce well.  Emphasized
by the news media and the academic classes - both of whom believe
it's wonderful to spend somebody else's money - the result has
been a focus for the last 70 years on the notion that if only
we accepted the finite limit of wealth and then redistributed
it, everybody would be better off.
<P>
In truth, the objective, historic, long-term fact is that societies
that focus on creating wealth outstrip societies that focus on
redistribution in improving the lot of the poorest people.  That's
an objective fact historically.  Societies that focus on getting
rich bring everybody up at a dramatically faster rate than societies
that focus on redistribution. In fact, if you try to raise the
bottom in a static model you rapidly get resistance from everybody
else, because, by definition in a static model, only achieving
it not by sharing the new wealth, which people are rather comfortable
doing, but by taking away from people what they already have.
<P>
Thus my core critique of the left as I think it is emerging in
the late 20th century is that: first, the state central planners
have failed; second, secular bureaucracies don't transform people;
and third, emphasizing redistribution is a dead loser in helping
the poor compared to focusing on the production of wealth.  This
leads me to seven principles that may be peculiarly an American
formulation.
<P>
First, that there's a spiritual basis of freedom.  There's a reason
that the Founding Fathers said we're endowed by our Creator. 
In fact, being human is a spiritual, not a biological fact, and
may be the most important thing that distinguishes us from purely
biological organisms.  If you don't have a system that says there's
a spiritual basis for being human, you have only a lawyer's definition
of human rights and that's a very shallow framework.  
<P>
Second is that we believe in the power of technological advance
to increase the potential for human goals. You get a better environment
over time and a better approach to helping the poor with a higher
technology society rather than with a Luddite approach. The truth
is that if you go back to the beginning of the Neolithic period,
over time and as a general principle, more technology is better
than less.  On balance technology tends to be used more for good
even though it can also produce gun powder and atomic weapons.
 
<P>
Third, the power of the entrepreneur and the free market to create
wealth is extraordinary.  Whenever possible it needs to be optimized.
 Entrepreneurs and the free market are likely to create more wealth
for more people and therefore over time actually improve a lot
of the poor better than either redistribution or secular bureaucracies.
 
<P>
Fourth is the importance of the individual and families.  That
is the core argument for tax cuts: who spends your money better,
you or a secular bureaucracy? We don't emphasize the moral content
behind tax cuts enough.  This is a moral fight.  Should you have
the right to your resources or should somebody you've never met
have the right to your resources, and if so, what's their claim?
 Why should they have the right to take from you? Yet we lack
the courage because we are still in a leftist world in which we
believe the money belongs to the government and who are we to
give you back your own money.  I think we need to be much more
aggressive and much more assertive in saying there's a moral basis
for tax cuts.  It's called individual freedom and the right of
families to spend their own money.  
<P>
Fifth is the power of volunteerism, which is in many ways a peculiarly
American contribution to the modern world.  Best described by
de Tocqueville, it is another argument for lower taxes.  How can
you be a volunteer if you're indentured to the state? If we want
more volunteerism, we need to leave more resources with those
who would volunteer.  It's a moral cause that requires we ask:
which does a better job of helping people, secular bureaucracies
or the variety of volunteer methods of reaching out?  
<P>
Sixth is the importance of appropriate government.  I am not an
extreme Libertarian.  I in fact believe there are many things
we want the government to do - protect our borders, stop the drug
trade, insure public health.  I'd like to make sure, for example,
that we don't go back to having yellow fever or malaria on a grand
basis.  These are not small things.  It is a very strong government
that can defend its borders, stop epidemics and maintain an honest
dollar.  I am for a strong government, but I'm for an appropriate
government. That means minimum bureaucracy, maximum free enterprise
and a tax code which encourages volunteerism and encourages families.
 
<P>
Lastly is the importance of language and grammar.  It goes back
in a sense to Orwell's argument in the <I>Politics in the English
Language,</I> which is an essay that every would-be revolutionary
should read.  The fact is that the left steals our language. 
The left defends the most grotesque destruction of human beings
in the modern social state by arguing that we would be cruel to
the poor by liberating them from the very shackles which the leftists
fasten on them.  I can imagine nothing worse for an American child
than subjecting them to the welfare system of Washington, D.C.,
and it's not for lack of money.  It is because the system is inherently
destructive of human beings. I can imagine nothing more liberating
for the children of Washington than to abolish their schools tomorrow
morning and replace them with a scholarship for every child of
$9,000 and allowing them to go to any school that wants to charge
them and actually teach them how to read and write.  
<P>
<h3><a name="rev">The Conservative Revolution</a></h3>
<B>by <a href="#redw">John Redwood </a></B>
<P>
With so many conservatives meeting to discuss revolution, it's
as if Edmund Burke could turn up at the Communist International.
 Should I be meeting like this with all of you with such an agenda?
 Yes, of course I should and we should, for only those who recognize
the revolutionary power of change as we hurtle toward the next
millennium have a chance of seizing the democratic mandate and
of conserving what is best in our traditions.
<P>
It was not we conservatives, after all, who unleashed the dynamic
hurricane of the third industrial revolution, nor was it western
conservatives who carried a keynote to government in the Philippines,
took to the streets in Romania and swept aside the Communists
or who tore down the blocks in the Berlin Wall hand by hand. 
It was the force of the people themselves in all their infinite
ingenuity and their diversity.  It was we conservatives who stood
firm for the principles and truths which now inspire so many around
the world, the truths of free trade, freedom under the law, of
one man, one vote.  We owe President Reagan and Prime Minister
Thatcher a debt of gratitude for standing up to the mighty U.S.S.R.
and precipitating its collapse from within while the Liberals
would have none of it, and if they had had none of it, we would
live in a much less interesting world.  
<P>
The mighty forces of change have given us hope for a better world,
a world free of Communist tyranny, a world where more look to
the ballot box to resolve their differences, a world where more
can hope to enjoy the fruits of global capitalism.  Never have
so many looked forward to such riches before.  
<P>
But those same forces have generated great feelings of insecurity
in western electorates.  So fast is change that people fear for
their own jobs.  Where will I be working next year they ask. 
What new things must I learn to carry on working?  Will I have
a job at all?  In the United States and the United Kingdom, fears
about jobs are allied to worries about the stability of the traditional
family.  All too many children will go to bed tonight in New York
or in London in a home with no father.  All too many children
are born into a home which has never known the presence of a father.
 And all too many modern marriages are straining to breaking point.
 
<P>
In such a world, voters look to politicians not just to lead a
revolution, but to reassure.  They want us to waive magic wands
to remove the uncertainties.  They see a bloated public sector
that is arrogated itself men, money and management in a stunning
array of powers, services and agencies.  They expect such a colossus
to help and protect them, but all too often they are bitterly
disappointed.  
<P>
Free schooling may be provided but some children fall further
and further behind because they are not well taught.  Free health
care is provided but only sometimes if you're prepared to queue
and wait a year.  Each subsidy in government intervention fails
to stop redundancies.  Incomes are taxed ever more highly to meet
the unsatiable demands of the expanding state.  The numbers on
welfare grow as more miss out on the technological roller coaster.
 
<P>
It was that American, John Kenneth Galbraith, who complained of
private affluence and public squalor as he rallied a former generation
to a program of more government.  Today we are running the risk
of private squalor and public affluence.  We have certainly reached
in many western societies public waste and enforced private prudence.
 The take home pay of government and the numbers on its payroll
has far expanded far more rapidly than that of most others.  
<P>
People feel let down by many traditional politicians.  As government
has grown, there has been a wish to hold office but shuffle off
responsibility.  In Europe, the European Commission is never to
blame for anything.  When something goes wrong, it seeks others
to be scapegoats.  Many politicians now wish to make elections
matters of image and presentation rather than of substance.  The
sound bite rules the airways even though it may not come from
the heart of he who uttered it and rarely comes from his pen.
 As a result, the people, the electors, come to fell manipulated,
cheapened or cheated.  
<P>
Conservatives must never lose faith in the people, and we must
never lose the faith of the people.  We must look them in the
eye and we must tell them the truth.  Spin doctors should not
be paid to lie, for that way only breeds mistrust.  I believe
a conservative revival is not only possible but vital to the continued
prosperity, discipline and success of advanced societies.  Newt
Gingrich has shown how quickly people will return to our colors
if they are held high and if the army is given a sense of direction.
 For the army to march, for the conservative's recruiting sergeant
to flourish, it needs clear principles, a record of success, a
strategic as well as a tactical purpose.  Only a conservative
agenda can today deliver this.
<P>
The first task of conservatives is to conquer government itself,
to gain some control over the scale and complexity of modern administration.
 Government has to be brought to answer and to bow to the court
of the people.  
<P>
The second task is to cut taxes as the cost of government come
down.  Advanced countries cannot compete with the developing world
if their tills are raided too often by the tax gatherer.
<P>
The third task is to remove obstacles to business success.  We
need freedom from too many rules and regulations so that enterprise
has a chance. Fourth is to ensure that the tax, benefit and legal
systems put families first, buttressing them rather than undermining
them.
<P>
The fifth task is to promote global trade and welcome the third
industrial revolution.  It will generate many more jobs.  It makes
working from home possible.  It could empower the house bound,
liberate the busy, even enliven the bored.  It is more opportunity
than threat.
<P>
Finally, the sixth task is to be true conservatives in protecting
and embellishing all that is best in our different inheritances.
 For Britain, that means the English language, our ancient and
modern noisy democracy, and our great institutions from Oxford
University to Botts Hospital now 900 years young.  For the United
States, that means living up to the sonorous words of Washington,
Jefferson and Lincoln on the rights of man and the pursuit of
happiness.  And for Canada, that means keeping together their
special federation and preserving Canadian identity, for a sense
of belonging matters more today than ever.    
<P>
As conservatives who understand the third industrial revolution,
we are not promising people an end to commercial change.  We cannot
and will not stand like some modern King Kanute and demand that
the software recedes.  We must embrace technological change and
free our people to prosper from it.  But to reassure them, we
must keep alive the flames of our own unique constitutions.  We
must remind people why they belong to families and communities
as well as to the global marketplace.  They gain their security
from the one and their prosperity from the other.  
<P>
Many of you must remind Americans why they should be proud of
America from sea to shining sea.  I must remind my fellow countrymen
why we should be proud to be British with the mother of parliaments
and mother of the free.
<P>
<h3><a name="japan">The Japanese Restoration</a></h3>
<P>
<B>by <a href="#mats">Iwao Matsuda </a></B>
<P>
Revolution is not a word that we Japanese like to use with regard
to our country.  In 1868, when a dynamic group of young reformers
took over the government, abolished feudalism and created the
political, economic and educational institutions of a modern nation
state, they chose the word restoration, not revolution, to describe
what they were doing.  History calls their achievement the Meji
Restoration.  
<P>
Today, when once again Japan needs top to bottom changes in its
political, economic, educational and social institutions, the
key word is reform rather than revolution.  Yet clearly the changes
that Japan requires are revolutionary.  If our program succeeds,
we will have brought about a revolution that will complete what
began with the Meji reformers more than 100 years ago.  It will
embody the most far reaching changes that our country has ever
known and enable us to join the ranks of  the world's normal democratic
states.  
<P>
What is a normal democratic state?  It is first of all a democracy.
 What we have in Japan today is democracy a la Japanese.  We have
the institutional forms of parliamentary government but the circumstance
is rather different from what is regarded as normal in American
and European democracies.  Ours is based on consensus politics
and a mentality that tends to exclude outsiders.  The goal of
the New Frontier Party is to bring about in government alteration
between two political parties that will compete with each other
on the basis of policy, not factions or personalities.  
<P>
For almost the entire post-war period, a single party - the Liberal
Democrats - held exclusive power.  Their monopoly was broken in
July 1993, when a group of reform minded Liberal Democrats rebelled
against the party leadership and established a new party.  I was
one of those Liberals.  Together with other opposition parties,
we won the general election and established a coalition government.
 Yet soon the Liberal Democrats made a deal with their sworn enemies,
the Socialists, and returned to power.  
<P>
To oppose what we regarded as this unholy alliance, all major
opposition parties except the Communists came together in December
1994 to establish the New Frontier Party.  Today, at least in
form, we have the beginning of a two party system.  On one side
stands the government, a coalition of Liberal Democrats, Socialists
and a minor party.  What holds this coalition together?  In my
view, it is a common desire to enjoy the perks  of government
power.  They mouth the slogans of reform but in fact they want
to keep their vested interests.
<P>
By contrast, the New Frontier Party is dedicated to the cause
of change.  We call for wide-ranging changes in politics, in the
economy, in education, in society.  In politics, we were partially
successful during our brief one year in power.  We changed the
election system from one of modified-seat election district to
one which has 300 single-seat constituencies and 200 proportional-representation
seats.  The first election under this system will be held sometime
before the summer of 1997.  It may not immediately bring about
a permanent two party system, but we are convinced that over time
minor parties will fade away.  The present Socialist Party will
be the top candidate for extinction.
<P>
The New Frontier Party's platform calls for clear choices in politics.
 We want to end government by bureaucracy and bring about government
by the people's elected legislators.  We will reduce the number
of ministries from 20 today to 15 after we come to power, and
we will have legislators taking a much more active load in their
ministry.
<P>
Our partnership with the United States is primary (of course with
Canada and England also).  The Cold War has ended but East Asia
remains a dangerous and uncertain place.  China is a huge question
mark, but more unpredictable and therefore more dangerous is North
Korea.  Asia needs the American security presence.  Yet the Japan
we want is one where we assume a much more active partnership
than the existing government.  We will raise our voice louder.
 We may not always agree with the United States, but we will never
forget that we are allies.  We want a permanent seat on the United
Nations Security Council, and we pledge to play a leading role
in its affairs.  The United Nations is far from perfect, but it
is the only international forum we have, and we want to be active
to make it better.  We will not shy away from peace keeping duties.
<P>
At home, we want small government at the center and more power
devolved to local entities. We will have about 300 local authorities
nationwide, small enough to be close to the borders, large enough
to carry out effective government, for which we will replace the
present hodgepodge of 47 prefects and more than 3,200 cities,
towns and villages.
<P>
In the economy, the principal weapon for reform will be deregulation.
 We have no illusions about the difficulty of our task.  Japan
has been a regulated society for more than 1,000 years.  We have
a lot of people, little land, and few natural resources for everyone
to share in an economy of scarcity.  There have to be regulations
and on whole people have accepted these regulations.  In modern
times, the concept of fairness, of equality, has taken precedence
over the concept of individual freedom.  We are a society without
large gaps between rich and poor, management and it's workers.
 We would like to keep it so, but not at the cost of stifling
individual freedom and individual initiative.  We want to experience
the kind of wave that has lifted the American economy and keeps
it far ahead of the others.  That is a wave that does not depend
upon manufacturing production. We need better ideas.  We need
better information.  We need to know how to put information to
work in a more efficient way for each one of us.  In short, we
need freedom.
<P>
I say this is a difficult task because most of us recognize the
need for change.  Many are afraid of living in a society with
few regulations, in a society where each individual will have
to be more self-reliant and take greater responsibility for his
own actions.  Nevertheless, there's no other way for Japan to
move into the 21st century and survive unless people become convinced
that the only alternative to deregulation is continued decline
and eventual extinction.
<P>
Educational reform may be the most important of the reforms we
propose.  Universal education involves one of the great achievements
of the Meji reformers.  Japan today is one of the world's most
literate nations, but our education remains in the 19th Century.
 It emphasizes rote line, stuffing the student with all sorts
of relevant and irrelevant information which he can regurgitate
in written examinations.  We need education that will foster self-reliance
and individual creativity.  The primary emphasis must be allowing
the individual to develop.  Education is an area which we may
not see results for 10 years or more, but we must begin now for
we are already far behind the leaders in this field.  
<P>
Underlying all these reforms is a need for a change in society
itself. How do we move from decisions by consensus into the essence
of democracy?  This is a making by the majority.  Ultimately,
we can only achieve our goals by a revolution within each individual
consciousness.  That takes time, but that is a task to which we
have dictated ourselves.
<P>
<h3><a name="three">The Three Revolutions</a></h3>
<P>
<B>by <a href="#mann">Preston Manning </a></B>
<P>
Our subject is a world in revolution.  Reformation might be the
gentler word.  Perhaps we can talk about revolution through reformation;
that's the Canadian way of seeking the middle. I begin by asking,
which revolution are we talking about? I ask this because it seems
to me there are several revolutions going on in the world at the
same time, and it is important to distinguish them and to think
through the relationship between them.  
<P>
The first revolution is the conservative revolution, the rejection
of Socialism, of liberal interventionism, of the ideology of the
master state in favor of market based solutions to economic problems,
of more personal responsibility for social security, balanced
budgets and limited governments. Examples, of course, of this
revolution are the factory example in Great Britain and the Contract
with America, a program of the new Republicans here in Washington.
 
<P>
In my country, Canada, this conservative revolution is also in
progress, but proceeding more slowly and sporadically, which is
the Canadian way.  We start, of course, with revolution; is it
a provincial or federal responsibility? At the provincial level
it is being led by conservative parties in the Province of Alberta
and the Province of Ontario, but at the national level the federal
Conservative Party has virtually disappeared.  Therefore, at the
national level the conservative revolution is being managed or
mismanaged by a pragmatic liberal administration that is not at
all enthusiastic about leading such a revolution but is being
pushed along by a third party, namely, the Reform Party.  If all
of this sounds confusing, it is, but it arises from the fact that
we Canadians are extreme moderates and tend to protect ourselves
from the excesses of revolutions by entrusting their management
to people who do not believe in them.  
<P>
So that's a synopsis of the conservative revolution that is in
progress in our country, but there is another revolution which
is going on in the world at the same time. There have been allusions
to it by other speakers, and this I will refer to as the structural
revolution, and in my country, this revolution is as pronounced
as the conservative revolution.  
<P>
The structural revolution has two conflicting components.  On
the one hand it is characterized by the removal of the internal
and external barriers to trade, the aggregation of local and provincial
economies into national economies, and then the aggregation of
those national economies and identities into larger global structures
like the North American Free Trade Area, the European Union or
the Asia Pacific Economic Community.  At the same time that the
aggregation into bigger and bigger units is going on, of course,
more and more people and more and more countries want to affirm
and exercise more local and personal control over social services
and cultural policies that directly affect the quality of their
own lives and their cultural and personal identities.  Thus, in
that respect, they identify more with smaller and more homogeneous
units of political organization - local governments and communities
- based often on regional or racial or linguistic or cultural
distinctiveness.  
<P>
In Canada, therefore, at the same time that our national economy
is being integrated into the North American global economy, this
structural revolution manifests itself in the form of regional
alienation in western Canada, Quebec separatism, talk of maritime
union in our atlantic provinces, provincial premiers demanding
more decentralization of federal power, and large municipalities
contemplating city-state status.  In other words, the ground behind
Canada, and I'd suggest many other countries, is moving in two
different directions, like the big crustal plates that geologists
tell us are the cause of earthquakes.
<P>
The challenge of governments includes the challenge of designing
structures capable of absorbing those stresses and strains. Five
years ago, the alignment of political parties in the Canadian
Parliament that could have been described on the traditional left-right-center
axis. Today it could be just as well described as consisting of
traditional federalists - mainly liberals - defending the old
nation-state structure, separatists from Quebec seeking extreme
devolution, and new federalists - reformers - seeking to create
the more flexible federal state that can handle both of these
forces in the 21st century.  
<P>
Perhaps both the conservative revolution and the structural revolution
are simply aspects of a broader revolution, the democratic revolution.
 For me it is this democratic revolution which is the ultimate
revolution and which should end up being the distinguishing revolution
of our times.  All over the world, ordinary people are seeking
to get more control in their own hands or in the hands of institutions
they can influence over the facts that most directly affect the
quality and content of their lives.  Thus they will support the
conservative revolution to the extent that it limits the spending
and taxing powers of governments and leaves more dollars in the
pockets of citizens, if this is done equitably.  They will support
the conservative revolution to the extent that it redresses the
intrusiveness of the liberal, social policy state, provided the
old intrusions are not replaced by new intrusions.
<P>
Public support for the structural revolution, for enlarging markets
to stimulate economic growth, to create better jobs for people
with higher incomes, and public support for strengthening the
power of local government at the expense of larger and more distant
governments, is also it seems to me a manifestation of this broader
democratic revolution. If those larger and more distant governments
necessary to manage our national and international affairs are
to retain their legitimacy, they must take steps both to facilitate
a new division of powers between themselves and the lower levels
of government and they themselves must become more democratic,
more representative, more accountable and more responsive to the
people that they serve.
<P>
I am personally supportive of the general direction of the conservative
revolution and the structural revolution, but I believe that their
success or failure will ultimately be measured by the extent to
which they serve the cause of the democratic revolution, a democratic
revolution which I suggest is happening in Canada and virtually
every other country in the world.

<br><p><br>
<I>
<b><a name="webe">Vin Weber</a></b> is distinguished senior fellow at The Progress & Freedom Foundation, where he leads its Center for Political Renewal.  He is a former six-term Congressman from Minnesota.
<p>
<a name="ging"><b>Newt Gingrich</a></b> is Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives.  He has served the sixth Congressional district of Georgia since 1979.
<p>
<a name="redw"><b>John Redwood</b></a> is a Member of the British House of Commons.  He challenged Prime Minister John Major for the leadership of the Tory Party in 1995.
<p>
<a name="mats"><b>Iwoa Matsuda</b></a> is Director of Japan’s New Frontier opposition party.  A former Director at the Ministry of International Trade and Finance, he was elected to the Diet from the Gifu Prefecture in 1986.
<p>
<a name="mann"><b>Preston Manning</b></a> was elected to the Canadian House of Commons in October 1983 as the MP for Calgary Southwest.  He has been the Leader of the Reform Party of Canada since its founding in November 1987.
</i><p><br><p>
</blockquote></ul>
