<head>
<title>Editor's Roundup - February 1996 --NMP</title>
</head>
<body>
<h2>Editor's Roundup</h2><P>
<h3>February 1996</h3><p>
<img src="red-line.gif">
<P>

<P>
EDITOR'S PAGE<BR>

<P>
As our cover design illustrates,
the Republican Party presently has a serious public relations
problem. It is viewed as being too heavily weighted toward balancing
budgets and too light on compassion; in other words, out of balance.
<P>
Regarding the current budget debate,
polls show the largest share of the public--about 44 percent--blames
the Republican-controlled Congress for the paralyzing federal
government shutdown, a third blame President Clinton and about
half as many blame both.
<P>
In many regions once hostile to
Clinton, bumper stickers proclaiming, &quot;Clinton! At Least
He Cares,&quot; have replaced the more familiar, &quot;Impeach
Clinton.&quot;
<P>
&quot;The difficulty the Republican
Party faces,&quot; says Rob Mosbacher, a GOP activist in Texas
and son of the former Secretary of Commerce, &quot;is convincing
the American people that it is equally as enthusiastic about helping
people solve their problems as it is about cutting spending.&quot;
<P>
Author James Pinkerton agrees:
&quot;What the Republicans haven't done,&quot; says Pinkerton,
a former aide to President Bush, &quot;is convince the people
at the bottom half of the economy that there's something there
for them. I think they made a vision mistake by not going after
corporate welfare more energetically.&quot;
<P>
But rather than shore up their
credentials as good fiscal managers, the negotiations and subsequent
shutdown have instead made them look irresponsible and inept.
According to <I>U.S. News &amp; World Report</I>, preliminary
estimates suggest that the three-week episode cost at least $1
billion--on top of the estimated $700 million price tag for the
more extensive shutdown that lasted four working days last November.
<P>
The lack of balance in the GOP
message may explain the recent surge of Malcolm &quot;Steve&quot;
Forbes in Iowa and New Hampshire presidential polls. Although
Forbes has seemingly insurmountable political liabilities--being
the son of a wealthy man, having inherited hundreds of millions
of dollars, and possessing no elective experience--voters long
for a positive, upbeat message, which the millionaire publisher
provides along with his controversial flat tax proposal.
<P>
The remainder of the GOP presidential
field, including front-runner Sen. Robert Dole of Kansas, would
hardly be called an inspirational bunch. With the exceptions of
Lamar Alexander and Sen. Richard Lugar, they seem to be driven
more by the politics of fear, blame and resentment, than by optimism,
idealism or vision.
<P>
But there are some bright spots
on the Republican horizon. There are some GOP pols who understand
that perception is indeed reality. Freshman Rep. Sam Brownback
of Kansas blunted some voter outrage in his district by giving
back his pay during the first shutdown and setting up an escrow
account for it during the second.
<P>
Republican Sen. Dan Coats of Indiana
has authored a 19-part legislative agenda called the Project for
American Renewal, which includes a $500 tax credit for charitable
gifts. &quot;We need to reorient people back to what effective
compassion really means.&quot;
<P>
And Empower America founder Jack
Kemp recently unveiled recommendations for a single, low tax rate
for all Americans. Kemp and 13 others formed the National Commission
on Economic Growth and Tax Reform last year, at the behest of
Dole and House Speaker Newt Gingrich to unify Republicans on the
question of taxes.
<P>
In his comments at the Jan. 17
press conference where the commission's report was released, Kemp
stressed the importance of relieving the tax burden on the poor
and on working men and women. The former Secretary of Housing
and Urban Development is widely known--and is sometimes criticized--for
his ability to empathize with Americans at all income levels.
<P>
To turn around the public perception
that Republicans are mean-spirited, party leaders need to secure
more media exposure for spokespersons like Brownback, Coats, Kemp
and others who understand that, to become a majority party, they
must get votes not only from avowed conservatives, but from moderates
and independents as well.
<P>
Our three contributors to this
discussion of the GOP are all members of the party themselves.
Lynn Martin is a former congress member and was Secretary of Labor
during the Bush administration. Martin expresses confidence that
the GOP is aware of its errors and is working to correct them.
<P>
Walley Naylor is executive director
of the Mississippi Christian Coalition. In his piece, Naylor writes
that the party once represented a beacon of hope, but today &quot;that
beacon has burned out.&quot;
<P>
Jerry T. Burley ran unsuccessfully
in 1994 as the Republican nominee for Texas' 18th Congressional
District. Burley posits that the public's perception of party
members as a whole takes a toll on the prospects of those who
run for office championing the GOP banner.
<P>
Interestingly, all three link
the Republican Party's image of being insensitive toward the poor
to its failure to attract a significant portion of black votes.
<P>
<I>Gwen Daye Richardson</I>
<P>
<I>Editor<BR>
</I>

[ <a href="/nmp/">Home</a> | <a href="i-col.html">Index</a> ]<br>
</body>
