<HEAD>

<TITLE>Republican Dreaming -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>Republican Dreaming</h2>
by <a href="/pff/people/staff.html#O_Donnell">Richard F. O'Donnell</a>
<P>
 Today, two zealous camps dominate public discourse over our future.
Techno-utopian Pollyanna's are busy proclaiming the unadorned
good of information technology while the neo-Luddites oppose the
same technological change.
<P>
 Between these two groups are the vast majority of Americans,
who do not quite understand all the hype over the Internet, know
that ATM machines are convenient, but do not want their jobs automated
away.  The message Americans are waiting to hear is that through
all the dislocation and turmoil caused by the coming of the Knowledge
Age are tremendous opportunities for better lives, and that the
ideas which made this nation great can still work in the future.
<P>
 This may explain the amazing number of Republicans one encounters
these days who have basically written off the 1996 Presidential
election, conceding a second term to a man who by almost all measures
does not merit one.  Clinton's poll numbers may be up and he threw
effective tactical roadblocks in the budget battle, but why this
sense of defeatism?
<P>
Republicans should be excited and full of anticipation at completing
what they began in 1994:  the destruction of the Democratic party
as the governing majority in American politics. To do deliver
a knock-out punch in 1996, Republicans need to offer as a challenger
to Bill Clinton a candidate who addresses Presidential - not Congressional
- issues.  Dick Lugar was exactly right when he said that all
the candidates for the GOP nomination want to balance the budget,
restore the 10th Amendment and overhaul the tax code.  The problem
is, these are <I>not</I> the issues with which to win the Presidency.
<P>
 What won Ronald Reagan the White House in 1980 was not his list
of top three public policy priorities (stronger defense, lower
taxes and balanced budget), but the sense that he could make America
stand tall again.  He offered the hope and optimism for a better
future to a nation suffering, as Carter put it, the malaise of
the 1970s.
<P>
 The leadership Americans want from the Presidency is one which
transcends the public policy debate and from a moral high ground
offers America a principled vision on how to build a better future.
 Many Republicans respond that they do have a national figure
offering just such leadership:  Newt Gingrich.  Yet Newt Gingrich
is Speaker, and although he amazingly used that office during
the past year to become, in essence, America's head of government,
his job is still necessarily partisan and deals primarily with
tactical public policy issues.  Only a President with the skills
and - Clinton's weakness - moral authority, can don the mantle
of Head of State, transcend partisan politics and lead the majority
of Americans.
<P>
 Republicans who say &quot;we just need to nominate someone who
won't stop the Revolution and let Newt continue to supply the
vision&quot; are handing Bill Clinton the election.  The Republicans'
dilemma is a Speaker who talks like a President and Presidential
candidates who talk like Congressmen. Only a candidate whose message
is of Presidential caliber stands a chance of beating Clinton
- and saying &quot;Newt's the leader of the Revolution and I'm
with him&quot; is not of that level.
<P>
 Lost last fall amongst all the uproar over Clinton's national
&quot;funk&quot; gaffe was a theme to which he returned in his
State of the Union address and that comes close being a full-fledged
vision.   In September he said that it is the President's job
to lead Americans through the &quot;tumult and upheaval&quot;
of the information-saturated 1990's.  In the seventh paragraph
of the State of Union - before he said the era of big government
is over - Clinton said:  &quot;We live in an age of possibility.
A hundred years ago we moved from farm to factory.  Now we move
to an age of technology, information and global competition. 
These changes have opened vast new opportunities, but they also
present stiff challenges.&quot;  Alvin Toffler or Newt Gingrich
could not have said it better.
<P>
 Yet none of the candidates for 1996, including Clinton, are offering
a realistic vision of America in the Knowledge Age.  Through his
veneer Clinton is as obsessed with stagnating real wages as Bob
Dole is with the fact that it's &quot;his turn,&quot; as Phil
Gramm is with economics, as Dick Lugar is with nuclear terrorism,
and as Steve Forbes is with &quot;Voodoo II.&quot;
<P>
 All these messages fail to adequately address the disquiet Americans
feel about their nation's future in the Knowledge Age.  Does Windows
'95 herald an information driven renaissance, or are millions
of people going to be driven out of work by increased computerization?
 Pat Buchanan is the only GOP candidate remotely addressing these
issues; he is tapping into a true vein of anxiety among voters.
 Unfortunately, Buchanan is offering up neo-Luddite solutions
that are merely a reaction at being left behind as the future
arrives.
<P>
Americans aren't sure where their nation is headed, and are looking
for a Presidential candidate to honestly describe the nature of
our times.  The New Deal era provided us with a vision -- interstate
highways, television, moon landings -- that to a stunning degree
was realized.  Yet this success was bittersweet, because once
we achieved its promises, we had no replacement vision and consequently
lost our sense of direction.
<P>
 This calls for reinventing the American Dream for a new century,
which is tricky business. Irving Kristol recently identified one
reason:  &quot;America has come of age, the American dream has
been fulfilled to the degree that any dream ever is&quot;.  When
you've fulfilled your dreams, it is tempting to sit back and dream
no more.  The dream Kristol believes fulfilled -- and thus no
longer useful -- is one created for 20th century industrial America.
What we need now is a Dream for 21st century Knowledge-Age America.
<P>
 Currently none of the Presidential candidates is offering America
a new Dream. Democrats dream about high wages and universal health
insurance whereas Republicans dream of making a bundle. &quot;Necessities
or securities, but hardly the stuff of dreams,&quot; said <I>The
Nation</I>. The problem with both parties is that they are pecuniary.
<P>
 Yet, when all is said and done, Americans are Americans for reasons
larger than a dollar. Yes, we all want to be prosperous.  Yes,
we all want a less burdensome tax code.  But we hold other ends
in higher esteem.  Americans enjoy the sense of meaning that comes
from belonging to causes outside themselves, whether a revolution,
settling the frontier or racing to the moon.
<P>
 The great challenge for us today, something worthy of a Dream,
is to take all the new tools of the Knowledge Age and use them
to build a better society while minimizing the disruption and
dislocation these same tools will engender as we replace the ways
of the industrial world.
<P>
 It is this void which is driving the radical middle in American
politics.  Our nation is searching for a new Dream, for a new
goalpost toward which to strive.  Americans are looking for a
President who talks about more than just the public policy issues
of balanced budgets, states' rights and tax code reform.  Americans
want someone to show them that through all the confusion and seeming
chaos, the electronic frontier beckons us toward ever greater
freedom, creativity, individuality, community and progress.  If
the Republicans want to win the Presidency this year, their nominee
must, in addition to discussing the proper size and scope of government
in society, engage Americans in a discussion about the future
of their society itself.
<P>
<I>Richard F. O'Donnell is director of communications at The Progress
&amp; Freedom Foundation.</I>

<P><br>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</HTML>
