<HEAD>

<TITLE>Broadcast Spectrum: Putting Principles First -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<i>January 31, 1996</i><P>
<h2>Broadcast Spectrum: Putting Principles First</h2>
by The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation's <a href="#board">FCC Working Group</a>
<P>
For the last several months, House and Senate conferees have worked
diligently to iron out differences between the telecommunications
bills passed by their respective bodies.  They have reached apparent
closure on a compromise that would begin the process of creating
a new telecom &quot;playing field&quot; based on policies of competition,
open entry and market forces.
<P>Recently, disagreements have arisen
on one of the bill's major provisions, which addresses the allocation
of a portion of the electromagnetic spectrum for use by broadcasters.
 These disagreements threaten to delay or even derail final action
on a bill which has the potential to generate tremendous benefits
for consumers.
<P>
As background, the FCC is proposing to allocate
6 MHz licenses in today's UHF TV band  for the development of
so-called &quot;Advanced Television&quot; (ATV)(1), a new digital
technology that has indeed shown great promise.  Enormous controversy
exists over how these licenses should be assigned.  The current
legislation would require the FCC to limit eligibility for these
licenses to existing broadcasters who would, at some unspecified
time in the future, return their current spectrum to the government
following a transition to the new digital system(2).  Others,
most notably Senator Dole, contend that the licenses should be
assigned on the basis of competitive bidding or auctions among
all comers, a move the FCC believes could generate $10 to $70
billion in revenues. 
<P>
What's gotten lost in this debate is principle,
and the principle is property.  The paramount goal of spectrum
reform should be to channel existing broadcast spectrum -- and
new, so-called ATV spectrum - to its highest and best use.  Auctions
are one of several necessary reforms.  Far more important is the
need to give spectrum users the marketplace freedom and incentives
to deploy spectrum and new digital technologies efficiently. 
Giving existing and new spectrum users more flexibility to use
their spectrum as they see fit (as long as they do not interfere
with their spectrum &quot;neighbors&quot;) will create strong
economic incentives for spectrum users to weigh the relative merits
of possible uses.  Such flexibility and incentives are best achieved
through property rights. 
<P>
Government ownership and micromanagement
of the broadcast spectrum dates to Herbert Hoover's decision in
1927 to expropriate the spectrum on behalf of the Federal government.
 Since that time, the government has meted out  limited duration
&quot;licenses&quot; allowing use of the spectrum only under the
tightest of government controls.  The centrally-planned FCC system
typified by the current approach to ATV lacks the market flexibility,
incentives and information necessary to direct spectrum to its
highest and best use.  Time and again,  the FCC has made overly
rigid spectrum allocations and impeded new technologies.  Indeed,
the administrative process has been used as a weapon against consumers
by existing competitors to disadvantage new entrants and innovative
technologies.
<P>
The solution to the current broadcast spectrum conundrum
is to recognize the error of Herbert Hoover's ways -- or at least
their obsolescence -- and return to a property rights regime for
the broadcast spectrum.
<P>
Specifically, broadcasters' rights to their
current spectrum should be recognized as property, pure and simple.
 They should be given, in effect, fee simple title to the spectrum
they now hold and be allowed to use it for any technology or service
customers want; or, if they prefer, to sell it to new owners.
<P>
As
for the new spectrum, it too should be relieved from government
control and returned to the private sector.  Auctions -- properly
constructed and without the myriad of special interest preferences
that have characterized previous auctions -- should be held as
soon as possible.  Winning bidders should also receive fee simple
title to their property, without restrictions on use.
<P>
Is such a
proposal politically viable?  Only the politicians can decide.
 But it would accomplish three important objectives.
<P>
Broadcasters
would be given something they do not now have -- an asset they
could use, borrow against or sell.  They would be able to use
their current spectrum for new technologies in entrepreneurial
ways currently prohibited by the FCC's licensing restrictions.
 And, if they decided they really do need the new spectrum to
make the transition to some new form of digital television, they
could borrow against the value of their current spectrum to capitalize
their participation in the auctions.
<P>
Deficit hawks would also get
their wish -- the near-term auction of the new spectrum.  And,
since the auction would now offer fee simple title, rather than
the government-limited licenses envisioned by the FCC, there is
every reason to believe it would generate even more money than
currently estimated.
<P>
Finally, and most important, the American
people would get back a small piece of what Herbert Hoover took
away in 1927, and take an important first step toward restoring
ownership of the entire electromagnetic spectrum to America's
entrepreneurial, innovative private sector, where it can contribute
to the prosperity potential of the information revolution.   Such
a step is essential to maintaining America's advantage in the
worldwide digital marketplace -- the fastest growing segment of
the global economy.<P><br>

<ol><small><li>Tentative Decision and Further Notice of Inquiry in MM Docket No. 87-268, 3 FCC Rcd 6520 (1988).
<br>*Members
of  the Working Group participated with the project solely in
their individual capacity and do not necessarily represent the
views and/or position of their respective institutions and/or
telecommunications affiliations.  Greg Sidak, who was unable to
review this work, and  Tom Hazlett, both of AEI, are members of
the Working Group but have not approved this commentary.
<li> The transition would involve not only the construction of digital broadcasting facilities but also the purchase by consumers of digital receivers (new TV sets, or converters for their current sets).  Such a transition could easily take a decade or more during which broadcasters would retain licenses to their current spectrum, so long as they continue broadcasting analog television signals.
</ol></small><P><br>

<a name="board"></a>
Dr. Robert Crandall, The Brookings Institution     
<br>Dr. Thomas Lenard, PFF                   
 <br>Dr. Jeffrey A. Eisenach, PFF           
<br> William C. Myers, PFF                 
<br>James Gattuso, Esq., CSE                
<br>Peter Pitsch, Esq., PFF &amp; The Hudson Institute                                
<br>Peter W. Huber, Esq., The  Manhattan Institute 	
