</DOCHDR>
<!doctype html public "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Reflections on the Revolution -- PFF</title>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>Reflections on the Revolution</h2>
By <a href="/pff/people/sfellow.html#Weber">Vin Weber</a>
</center><P>
<P>
<I>&quot;One has a feeling of going it blindly because we are
in a tremendous stream and none of us knows where we are going
to land.&quot;</I>
<br><I>       --Eleanor Roosevelt</I>
<P>
 As Americans prepare to vote in the forthcoming Presidential
election, our national politics is in turmoil.  The 1990s has
witnessed the greatest challenge to the legitimacy of the two
major parties in modern times.  George Bush went from stratospheric
approval ratings to losing the Presidency in a three-way race
in which Ross Perot received the largest percent of the popular
vote of any third party candidate since Teddy Roosevelt.  Yet
just two years later, the Clinton Presidency lay in shambles as
the Republicans took control of Congress for the first time in
40 years. The American electorate increasingly identifies not
with Republicans, nor with Democrats, but with a party that does
not (for all intents and purposes) exist -- the &quot;independents.&quot;
<P>
 As elected officials daily flee their membership in the Democratic
party, Americans are increasingly confused over whether the parties
stand for anything.  Is there such a creature as a &quot;New Democrat,&quot;
or is Bill Clinton's party still a high tax and spend coalition
of liberal interest groups?  Where are the Republicans heading,
toward the reactionary Buchanan or the futuristic Gingrich?  When
asked what percentage of promises they thought politicians typically
broke, Americans recently responded with the staggering total
of 78 percent.  During Ross Perot's mercurial Presidential challenge,
70 percent of the American people declared no confidence in either
political party.
<P>
 National politics during the 1990s is driven by the simple fact
that Americans believe, as Ross Perot so succinctly put it, &quot;the
government is broken and we need to fix it.&quot; Whether it is
the national debt, decaying inner cities or regulatory burdens,
 citizens feel that the Federal government is less an ally than
a threat to their making the good life.  Fewer than a third of
the American people believe that the government does the right
thing -- down from about 80 percent a couple of decades ago. 
The voters place the blame for this squarely on the seeming inability
of elected officials' from both parties to produce the necessary
changes.
<P>
Yet through all this confusion a new vision for the proper role
of government in society is emerging to replace the legacy of
the New Deal (the idea that centralization, bureaucracy and government
could solve every problem).  It is around the principles of the
information age that the vision of a New Majority coalition will
form and define a new era in American politics.
<P>
It is difficult to describe the new era because our political
discourse is still dominated by the language of the New Deal/Great
Society era.   Many political analysts still talk in terms of
stitching together a coalition of interest-based demographic groups.
 When Eleanor Roosevelt spoke the words above in 1932, the people
coming together to form the New Deal did not yet know where they
were going.  It took them a generation to develop the language
with which we today are so familiar.  Today's emerging New Majority
finds itself in much the same position as the First Lady --  they
know they are leaving the past behind and creating a new political
order, but they do not yet know where they will end up.
<P>
 Replacing an old political order is messy and confusing.  It
often seems as if the public is not sure exactly what it wants.
 On the one hand -- if you believe the results of the 1992 Presidential
election - the voters say they want an activist government.  Yet,
when they tried to create an  &quot;activist&quot; health care
system, President Clinton and the Democrats were rejected.  The
public then embraced a Contract with America that called for drastically
delimiting the power of the Federal government.  Taken as a whole,
these conflicting demands signal an era of change.
<P>
 American politics is no longer a fight over the size of New Deal
programs.  Since FDR, voters may have argued over how much should
be spent, but the majority of Americans never questioned the fundamental
principle of the New Deal:  that Federal government programs were
the appropriate way to solve America's problems, whether old-age
pensions through Social Security, the poor through welfare, or
pollution through the Environmental Protection Agency.  And the
truth be told, there was little reason for Americans to question
this principle because, by and large, the New Deal and its programs
<I>did </I>make the United States a better place to live.
<P>
 But today that is no longer so.  Social Security and Medicare
are near bankruptcy and will not be able to support the Baby Boomers
as they begin to retire early next century (now less than four
years away).  No longer is welfare helping widows and infants,
but instead facilitating an urban underclass that threatens to
tear apart America's social fabric.  And Federal regulations have
gone from the sensible to the absurd. The reason these programs
suddenly seem to be the problem rather than the solution is that
the world in which they were created no longer exists.
<P>
 American society is transforming itself away from the industrial
age that has dominated the past century just as surely as it moved
away from the agrarian age during the time of our nation's founding.
 &quot;Our age&quot; is yet to be determined.  We know that it
will be overwhelmingly influenced by the information technology
that is now upon us -- every day we hear something new about the
Internet, Cyberspace and virtuality.  This is already manifesting
itself in our politics.
<P>
The so-called Republican Revolution of 1994 occurred not on election
day but the moment President Clinton's bureaucratic and centralized
health care plan died in a Democratic Congress.  Americans rejected
an industrial age design being imposed upon them in the information
age.  Nothing demonstrated the death of the New Deal paradigm
more than President Clinton's recent balanced budget proposal.
 It was not the balanced budget per se that was important. It
was that the man who campaigned as a &quot;New Democrat&quot;
capitulated to the philosophical direction of the New Majority.
It was no longer a debate about increasing government spending,
taxation or centralization of programs (like health care) but
about a totally new political direction - smaller, less centralized
government.
<P>
Just as the election of Eisenhower did not mean the end of the
New Deal's philosophical hegemony, neither would Bill Clinton
or any other candidate's election in 1996 mean the end of the
emerging principles of the New Majority. As all successful revolutionaries
know:  There comes a time to stop the revolt, know you have destroyed
the old order, and begin building a new one.
<P>
<B>The Role of Government: Devolve, Diffuse and Connect Through Competition &amp; Community</B>
<P>
 The outlines of the principles on which to build the new political
age are becoming clear.  The bureaucratic, centralized government
design will be replaced because the information age demands a
new organization. As General Motors, IBM and AT&amp;T have learned,
decentralization and human capital are the hallmarks of the new
age.  While the private sector has been learning this lesson for
more than a decade, government and academia have been the last
to understand the new era.
<P>
The three major trends that will enable this to occur in the new
era will be devolution, diffusion and connection. Devolution is
sending power and responsibility to the lowest level possible
for effective decision-making.  Shifting from federal to state
or local control is just a trickle today. Within a few years it
will be a flood. The pioneering efforts of such states as Wisconsin
and Michigan will be recognized as the beginning. If Medicaid
and Welfare are returned to the states, this trend will have been
firmly established.
<P>
 Diffusion is relying on non-governmental organizations or individuals
to perform many of the functions government usurped during the
industrial era.  The use of vouchers, privatization, voluntary
organizations, charities and churches are among the tools of diffusion.
Cities such as Indianapolis and Jersey City are building models
of diffusion.
<P>
I need to make one cautionary point about diffusion. Ronald Reagan
used to talk about how the &quot;dead hand of government&quot;
would stifle and cripple mediating institutions, and he was right:
Voluntary organizations' and charities' original social purposes
withered because of government's absorption of their functions
into the welfare state.  It is obvious that government cannot
immediately withdraw from these functions and expect churches
and charities to automatically fill the void. These &quot;charitable
muscles&quot; have not been exercised in a long time, and there
must be a transition period during which government gives over
these responsibilities while charitable institutions regain the
skills and knowledge to reclaim their original purposes.
<P>
 The final trend is connection. This has less to do with government
than with individuals. We must return to the sense of community
we once had.  The most important people are those closest to you.
You must want to help -- and feel a responsibility for --  yourself,
your family, your friends and your neighbors. In this respect
I agree with Hillary Rodham Clinton's diagnosis of the problem:
It takes a village! I disagree totally with her prescribed cure:
 more intrusive government. Government cannot build villages;
it is more likely to raze them.
<P>
 To be able to devolve, diffuse and connect, America needs a serious
discussion about the role of government. As the disagreement with
Mrs. Clinton shows, this may be the definitive difference between
the evolving left and right in politics. It may take a Presidential
election as definitive as 1932 to cement the principles of the
New Majority as the reigning paradigm.
<P>
<B>The Ties that Bind: Our 21st Century Opportunity</B>
<P>
 The industrial era brought havoc to an unknowing and bewildered
populace.  Social norms and cultural promises were broken, the
economy shifted from one dependent on artisans and entrepreneurs
to one built by large-scale factories.  Workers moved from being
independent operators to cogs in assembly-line machines.  Individuals
lost control of their lives as it increasingly passed into the
hands of the experts, engineers and managers who determined the
rules of work.  These changes undermined people's  traditional
sense of order.  They scrambled for a new political paradigm that,
like the new factories, would emphasize mass programs, bureaucratic
control and order.
<P>
This order did not come to pass immediately. From the Progressives
at the turn of the century onward, an increasing number of Americans
began to coalesce around a conception of government and governance
that viewed centralized, bureaucratic programs as the appropriate
provider of solutions.  Yet it was not until the New Deal that
a majority of the electorate believed in this view of the role
of government, a conception that would dominate American politics
for the next 40 years.
<P>
The emerging majority realizes that the principles behind the
New Deal are dead, and voted for Republican control of Congress
in 1994 to bury its programs as well.  Yet this begs a question:
 What next?  If the animating spirit of the New Deal will not
work for this new information age, what will?  Is there a new
view about the role of the government in American life around
which a new political majority will form?
<P>
 The answers are still vague, but broad outlines seem to be coming
into focus.  Government, especially government in Washington,
will have a diminished, supportive role rather than the supreme
role it has enjoyed.  With the national government no longer seen
as the solution to all our problems, national politics will no
longer be a zero-sum game of who gets the next Federal program
enacted for their cause and who gets to impose their views on
whom.  Government will instead focus on empowering citizens and
the communities they form to solve their own problems.  Through
the use of vouchers and other tools, people will choose the best
means to achieve their goals, rather than be subject to the one-size-fits
all approach of today's government programs.  The vision of the
New Majority recognizes communities (mediating institutions) are
the strength and backbone of a healthy American civilization,
and pluralism the answer to competing values.
<P>
<I>Vin Weber is Distinguished Senior Fellow at PFF, where leads
its Center for Political Renewal.  He is writing </I>The New Majority:
Party Politics for the 21st Century<I>, to be released in the
spring of 1996, and from which this essay is derived.  The views
expressed are solely those of the author.</I>

</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
