<HEAD>
<title>Jacobs: Judge ideas by results, not intentions -- PFF</title>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Chris Pressley">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<h2>Judge Ideas by Results, Not Intentions</h2>
By <a href="/pff/jacob-io.html">Dr. Joseph J. Jacobs</a></center>
<P>
 My friend Sidney Hook, in his transition from a Marxist to its
most vociferous and effective critic, articulated the double-standard
applied by the left when evaluating socialism and capitalism.
<P>
&quot;I was guilty of judging capitalism by its operations and
socialism by its hopes and aspirations; capitalism by its works
and socialism by its literature,&quot; he explained.
<P>
I was most fortunate to know Sidney Hook, the renowned philosopher,
well enough to have a number of discussions and arguments with
him. I rarely prevailed in any arguments. The only time I came
close was when I asked him define his, then, current politics.
He said, &quot;Suppose I would call myself a democratic socialist,&quot;
reflecting, I thought, his reluctance to go all the way to &quot;conservative.&quot;
The word oxymoron had not been invented then, so I said, &quot;But,
Sidney, that's inherently self-contradictory.&quot; His terse
reply, &quot;You may be right,&quot; was as close as I ever came
to winning a point with him.
<P>
The socialist theoreticians are so used to comparing their theory
to other theories that they cannot bring themselves to evaluate
their theories in light of reality. In its 75 years, the great
Russian empire dominated a large part of the world and its reduction
of socialist theory to practice failed miserably.
<P>
Ask the convinced socialist or the passionate advocate of central
planning why he persists in promoting a system which has been
a demonstrated failure and the likely answer will be: &quot;If
only the right people had been involved, it could have worked.&quot;
<P>
They insist that there is nothing fundamentally wrong with the
system. It's just that the people in charge failed to implement
it properly. If only the right people (implied, &quot;such as
me&quot;) had been at the helm, things might have been different.
But that is the precisely the point. Men are imperfect - even
those that construct the most exquisite theories. Inevitably they
produce imperfect results.
<P>
The final test is always, in engineering terminology, reduction
to practice. Many wonderful things have resulted from well-intentioned
actions, but many harmful things have, too.  Equally, many great
things may not have been accomplished because of excessive caution.
<P>
It's tempting to describe these contracting impulses as mature
and immature, but that may be too judgmental.  We need the untrammeled
emotions to integrate ourselves from childhood to adulthood. 
But Having reached adulthood, must we lose our wonderment and
surrender to cynicism?
<P>
&quot;Maturity&quot; is the best balance btween the restrictive
obligations of the real world and the lack of restrain of our
youthful yearnings.  In phiosophic jargon, we have the classic
conflict between &quot;freedom&quot; and &quot;order.&quot;
<P>
That segment of society which nourishes the childhood yearning
in us, I choose to call the art world.  Those I inlude are, of
course, the artists, the composers, the craftsmen, but also those
who write -- newspapers, books, poetry, plays.  Inlude as well
the performers, screen and television actors, the sportsmen, the
musicians, the magicians, the jugglers and the comedians -- in
short, those who successfully stimulate our emotions.
<P>
These people all appeal primarily to our childlike instincts --
those of us that are uninhibited by the restrictions of civilized
society.  They are constructive and important parts of our adult
life when filtering out the dark, destructive sides of our instinctual
youthful behavior -- the &quot;childishness,&quot; if you will.
 Along with our maturity and sense of responsibility we accept
with joy and gratitude what these wonderful people have to offer
us.  For they nourish our emotions without any boudaries of inhibition.
<P>
An important segment of the conservative world also possesses
this childlike quality to some degree.  Inventors, scientific
leaders and entrepreneurs all have a childlike longing for daring
innovation.  But scientists are, at the same time, conservative
in their willingness to test their intuitive leaps in the laboratory.
<P>
Of necessity, those who appeal to our hearts so effectively, must
themselves have a connection or a sensitivity to the child in
all of us.  How else can they be effective?  How can they know
what our hearts yearn for?  Yet even they must be bound by the
dimensions of the real world.
<P>
Most thoughtful people reject the mechanistic concept of &quot;maturity&quot;
and recognize that the full life demands both it and the childlike
impulses of which dreams are made.  Liberal thought is less inhibited.
 Conservative thought is more constrained.  But neither liberals
nor conservatives have a monopoly on wishing things were better.
<P><P>
<i>Dr. Joseph J. Jacobs is founder and chairman of the board of Jacobs Engineering Group Inc. and author of &quot;The Compassionate Conservative&quot; and &quot;Anatomy of an Entrepreneur.&quot; He is a member of the
advisory board for the Center for Effective Compassion at the Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation</i>
<P>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</HTML>
