<HTML>

<HEAD>
<title>Jacobs:  The Trap of "Entitlement" Thinking -- PFF</title>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<h2>The Trap of 'Entitlement' Thinking</h2>
 By <a href="/pff/jacob-io.html">Dr. Joseph J. Jacobs</a></center><P>
If we are serious about tackling a problem that is leading our
country into ruinous debt, perhaps the best way to begin is by
redefining our terms.
<P>
Every responsible person in Washington - from President Clinton
to Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich and on down - now recognizes
that reining in the high costs of government means dealing with
the escalating costs of so-called &quot;entitlement&quot; programs.
<P>
Do Americans have a &quot;right&quot; to a certain standard of
living? Are they &quot;entitled&quot; to money earned by other
people? Does our society owe people happiness? Certainly we should
not let people starve. We should be charitable. But the difference
between charity and entitlement is vast.
<P>
For a generation, entitlements have been the &quot;untouchable&quot;
part of the federal budget - never subject to elimination, cuts
or even critical performance review, but automatically scheduled
for cost-of-living increases and authorized for &quot;such sums
as may be necessary&quot; to respond to changing economic conditions.
Entitlements have been funded by the federal government with something
of a blank check.
<P>
Spending on these &quot;mandatory&quot; programs comprise 47 percent
of the federal budget. Another 14 percent of the budget is earmarked
for interest payments -- another &quot;mandatory&quot; program.
Thus, the president and Congress have control over 39 percent
of the budget.
<P>
Social Security, which has been described as &quot;middle class
welfare&quot; is the most expensive entitlement program. Since
1965, annual expenditures have grown from $17.1 billion to $241
billion. Social Security costs have increased annually at a rate
of 8 percent since 1980. Medicare has grown even faster - at a
rate of 12 percent. And Medicaid costs have risen yearly at an
11 percent pace. With runaway spending like that, how long before
we no longer can bear the cost -- unless you believe in the myth
that we have unlimited resources.
<P>
If no changes are made in the Social Security and Medicare systems,
the government projects that Americans will be paying 30 percent
of their income in
<P>
 federal taxes just to support these two programs by the year
2030. Today, every American man, woman- and child owes $10,000
as their share of the national debt. By 2030, that share would
increase to $64,000.
<P>
Surely, something must be done - and soon. But is tinkering with
the current system the answer? I think not.
<P>
Entitlements by their very nature -- by definition - create new
rights for Americans never dreamed of by our founding fathers
and never held up for the scrutiny of a full and open public debate.
<P>
Think about it. What is the derivation of that word &quot;entitlement&quot;?
The dictionary suggests that it is a legal right to something
- it is something that has been earned.
<P>
Those in search of such services need only be a resident of the
country perhaps not even a citizen. Then the politicians, bureaucrats
or activists must discover that a need exists that has a strong
compassionate component.
<P>
Once these compassionately impelled needs are met by passing laws
and appropriating money, they become entitlements. The recipients
very rarely have done anything that should &quot;entitle&quot;
them to receive these benefits. Thus, compassionately motivated
help is converted by word manipulation to an &quot;Entitlement.&quot;
<P>
Most such entitlement programs start out modestly with the goal
of creating a &quot;safety net&quot; for the truly needy. But
they are quickly turned into &quot;rights&quot; and expanded almost
geometrically as the bureaucratic self-interest in growth takes
over.
<P>
The curious transition to the use of the word &quot;Entitlement&quot;
reflects the inherent power of words to affect emotions and frame
the terms of our national debate. To be &quot;entitled&quot; to
something, the government implies one has a right to it. In private
industry, however, these kinds of added payments are characterized
more accurately as &quot;benefits.&quot; Contrast &quot;Benefits&quot;
with &quot;entitlements&quot; and the emotional content is revealed.
Benefits are given, but entitlements are a collection of obligations.
<P>
The Declaration of Independence defined our rights as &quot;life,
liberty and the pursuit of happiness.&quot; Happiness is not a
right, only the pursuit of it is. Our founders understood that
when government offers any more, it creates dependency rather
than freedom. Thus, we will never solve our &quot;Entitlement&quot;
problem until we understand that none of us is owed anything just
because we are here.
<P>
<P>
<i>Dr. Joseph J. Jacobs is founder and chairman of the board of Jacobs Engineering Group Inc. and author of &quot;The Compassionate Conservative&quot; and &quot;Anatomy of an Entrepreneur.&quot; He is a member of the
advisory board for the Center for Effective Compassion at the Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation</i>
<P>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</HTML>
